        <div id="tab-governance" class="tab-panel">
            <h2>Inbound audit &amp; compliance governance</h2>
            <p class="desc" style="margin-bottom: 1.8rem;">Data protection and content policy enforced once, at the gateway, instead of re-implemented inside every app that calls a model.</p>

            <div class="grid-2">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <span class="card-tag">Data Loss Prevention</span>
                        <span class="status-pill pill-beta">Beta</span>
                    </div>
                    <h3>DLP scanning on prompts &amp; responses</h3>
                    <p>AI Gateway DLP reuses Cloudflare One's detection engines and detection profiles — the same predefined and custom profiles used for Gateway HTTP policy — to scan both request and response bodies in real time, with no TLS decryption or proxy setup required.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Per gateway policy outcome: <strong>Pass</strong>, <strong>Flag</strong> (findings logged, response still returned), or <strong>Block</strong> (provider response discarded, <code>400</code> returned).</li>
                        <li>Findings surface on the <code>cf-aig-dlp</code> response header and in gateway logs.</li>
                        <li>Streaming responses are buffered fully before scanning — factor that into time-to-first-token for latency-sensitive routes, or scope DLP to <strong>Request</strong>-only checks.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <span class="card-tag">Content policy</span>
                        <span class="status-pill pill-beta">Beta</span>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Guardrails on prompts &amp; model output</h3>
                    <p>Guardrails apply moderation policies to inbound prompts and outbound completions at the gateway, ahead of your application code — useful for enforcing a single acceptable-use policy across every model and provider behind the gateway.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Configurable per gateway, independent of DLP policy.</li>
                        <li>Applies uniformly regardless of which upstream model served the request.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <span class="card-tag">Enterprise audit</span>
                        <span class="status-pill pill-ga">GA</span>
                    </div>
                    <h3>Workers Logpush to R2 / SIEM</h3>
                    <p>Full request and response metadata — tokens, cost, latency, cache and DLP outcome — pushes continuously to your own storage or SIEM, independent of the AI Gateway dashboard retention window.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Feeds directly into Splunk, Datadog, or any Logpush-compatible destination.</li>
                        <li>Gives SecOps a durable, tenant-owned audit trail of LLM usage.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header">
                        <span class="card-tag">Key custody</span>
                        <span class="status-pill pill-beta">Beta</span>
                    </div>
                    <h3>BYOK — provider keys stored at the edge</h3>
                    <p>Provider API keys live in Cloudflare's Bring Your Own Keys store rather than in application config or environment variables, and are injected into upstream requests at the edge. Required for Dynamic Routing.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Removes provider secrets from client bundles, CI logs, and app servers.</li>
                        <li>Rotates centrally, per gateway, without a redeploy.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="tab-resiliency" class="tab-panel">
            <h2>High availability &amp; cost protection</h2>
            <p class="desc" style="margin-bottom: 1.8rem;">Caching, rate limiting, and routing rules configured once at the gateway and applied to every client that calls it.</p>

            <div class="grid-3">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">Caching</span><span class="status-pill pill-ga">GA</span></div>
                    <h3>Exact-match response cache</h3>
                    <p>The cache key is a SHA-256 hash of provider, endpoint, model, auth header, and the full request body — an exact match, not semantic. Ideal for bounded-option flows (menu-driven bots, repeated validation prompts), not free-form chat.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>cf-aig-cache-ttl</code> — override TTL per request, 60s to 1 month.</li>
                        <li><code>cf-aig-skip-cache</code> / <code>cf-aig-cache-key</code> — bypass or pin the cache key per request.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">Traffic control</span><span class="status-pill pill-ga">GA</span></div>
                    <h3>Fixed or sliding rate limits</h3>
                    <p>Cap requests per gateway over a time window. Fixed windows reset on a clock boundary; sliding windows evaluate the trailing period continuously, so bursts spanning a window edge are still counted.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Requests over the limit receive <code>HTTP 429</code> before reaching the provider.</li>
                        <li>Protects both your bill and your upstream provider quota.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">Routing</span><span class="status-pill pill-beta">Beta</span></div>
                    <h3>Dynamic Routing &amp; fallback</h3>
                    <p>A named, versioned flow — conditionals, percentage rollouts, rate/budget-limit nodes, model nodes — replaces a hard-coded model name. Call it as <code>dynamic/{route_name}</code> instead of a model string; publish a new version to change behavior with no app deploy.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Model nodes chain as automatic fallback on error or quota exhaustion.</li>
                        <li>Requires an authenticated gateway with keys stored via BYOK.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2>Response header reference</h2>
            <div class="table-container">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Header</th><th>Direction</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td><code>cf-aig-cache-status</code></td><td>Response</td><td><code>HIT</code> or <code>MISS</code> against the gateway cache.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>cf-aig-dlp</code></td><td>Response</td><td>DLP findings for the request, when DLP is enabled on the gateway.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>cf-aig-cache-ttl</code></td><td>Request</td><td>Per-request cache TTL override, in seconds.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>cf-aig-skip-cache</code></td><td>Request</td><td>Bypass the cache for this request entirely.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>cf-aig-cache-key</code></td><td>Request</td><td>Pin a custom cache key instead of the default request hash.</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <h2>Edge troubleshooting reference</h2>
            <div class="table-container">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Response code</th><th>Probable cause</th><th>Resolution</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td><strong>401 Unauthorized</strong></td><td>Missing/invalid provider credential, or gateway authentication enabled without a valid <code>cf-aig-authorization</code> token.</td><td>Check BYOK key status and gateway auth settings in the dashboard.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>429 Too Many Requests</strong></td><td>Gateway rate limit reached, or upstream provider quota exhausted.</td><td>Review the rate-limit window and method (fixed/sliding); raise gateway or provider limits as needed.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>400 (DLP block)</strong></td><td>DLP policy matched a detection profile and the policy action is Block.</td><td>Inspect <code>cf-aig-dlp</code> in logs; adjust the profile or switch it to Flag if blocking is too aggressive.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>502 Bad Gateway</strong></td><td>Upstream provider outage or malformed upstream response.</td><td>Confirm a Dynamic Routing fallback model node is configured for this route.</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="tab-whyedge" class="tab-panel">
            <h2>Why a distributed edge, not a local firewall</h2>
            <p class="desc" style="margin-bottom: 1.8rem;">A local firewall, reverse proxy, or self-hosted API gateway is a finite resource sitting at one (or a handful of) network location — it has a CPU budget, a connection-table size, and a link capacity. A global anycast edge network is architected differently: absorption capacity is distributed across hundreds of locations, so no single point has to carry the full weight of inbound traffic alone.</p>

            <div class="grid-2">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">The core problem</span></div>
                    <h3>Blocking a request still costs CPU</h3>
                    <p>Evaluating a rule and dropping a packet is still work. A single appliance — even one that correctly rejects every bad request — can be pushed toward saturation by sheer request volume, because the decision to say "no" still consumes the box's finite CPU, memory, and connection-table slots. High volume degrades legitimate traffic even when the security logic itself is flawless.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">The structural fix</span></div>
                    <h3>Push the decision to where the capacity is</h3>
                    <p>Anycast routes each request to the nearest edge location, so absorption is distributed across the network rather than concentrated at one appliance. Filtering, rate limiting, and DLP happen before traffic ever reaches your origin or your application's own network boundary — the choke point moves from "one box you own" to "a network built to be that boundary."</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">What this means here</span></div>
                    <h3>AI Gateway inherits that posture</h3>
                    <p>Rate limiting and DLP for your LLM traffic run on the same distributed edge, not on a box you provision and size yourself. You're not estimating capacity for a new choke point — you're placing policy on infrastructure whose job is absorbing exactly this kind of load.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header"><span class="card-tag">Scope note</span></div>
                    <h3>What this page won't do</h3>
                    <p>We don't publish capacity thresholds, request-volume figures, or the mechanics of stressing any specific firewall or edge network here — that's operational detail with obvious misuse potential, on either side of the conversation. If you need a real capacity or threat model for your environment, that's exactly what an architectural review is for.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2>A pragmatic path to adopting AI at the edge</h2>
            <p class="desc" style="margin-bottom: 1.8rem;">Most teams don't need every feature in this reference on day one. A sequencing that works for most enterprise rollouts:</p>
            <div class="table-container">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>What you turn on</th><th>Why this order</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td><strong>1. Observe</strong></td><td>Point existing calls at the gateway. Logging + Analytics only.</td><td>Zero behavior change — see real cost, latency, and provider mix before setting any policy.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>2. Protect cost</strong></td><td>Caching on bounded-prompt flows, rate limiting per key.</td><td>Cheapest win, lowest risk — no data-handling policy decisions required yet.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>3. Govern data</strong></td><td>DLP profiles on prompts/responses; BYOK for provider keys.</td><td>Now that you know real traffic shape, write policy against it instead of guessing.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>4. Build resilience</strong></td><td>Dynamic Routing with fallback model nodes.</td><td>Requires BYOK and stable traffic patterns from stage 3 to route against.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><strong>5. Scale governance</strong></td><td>Guardrails, per-team budget limits, multi-gateway segmentation.</td><td>Once one team's rollout is proven, replicate the pattern instead of reinventing it per team.</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>

